Cover crop shoot dry matter samples were collected within 3 d of final chemical termination in spring. Dry matter sampling consisted of clipping all cover crops at the soil surface within a 0.76 m by 0.50 m frame placed at three random locations within each plot. The frame was centered on the row of the previous crop with the long side perpendicular to the row direction. Samples were dried at 60 degrees C and weighed; cover crop shoot biomass dry weights were then scaled up to per-plot value using the size of the sampling frames. Acquired by email from Thomas Kaspar/Iowa State University.

Cereal rye aboveground biomass was sampled from one (30” x 24”) quadrat at the soil surface within each plot just prior to rye termination and dried at 60 degrees as you have described.  Soil sampling from 0-15 cm was done in the fall prior to manure application (and cover crop application), one sample per experimental blocks (4 blocks) with 6 composite samples per block. Soil organic matter was determined at the UW-Madison Soil and Forage Analysis Lab following standard protocols (https://extension.missouri.edu/publications/sb1001). Acquired via email from Matt Ruark/University of Wisconsin.

Cereal rye aboveground biomass was sampled using a 0.25 m2 quadrat. Plants were cut within 1 cm of the soil surface, placed in paperbag and dried at 50 C for 3 to 5 days. Dry weight was recorded within 1 hour of coming out of the drying room. Acquired via email from Mark Van Gessel/University of Delaware.
